Rating: 3
My husband and I agree that this is a dish you could serve company. He had to ask what the meat was as he wasn't sure if it was pork or turkey. I used a white balsamic vinegar to keep the sauce lighter in color so that it didn't hide the turkey, and it made a very nice presentation. I would suggest using a non-stick pan with a tsp. of olive oil for frying the cutlets and adding the Tbsp. of butter to round out the sauce before serving. Still low fat, but gives a richness to the sauce without extra calories.

Rating: 1
I found the sauce to be too sharp, with a very strong predominance of the balsamic vinegar. Much better, in my view, is a similar sauce, also on this site, in the recipe for roast pork tenderloin with cranberry and balsamic vinegar sauce. I am going to try making that using cherries instead of cranberries to top the turkey cutlets.

